Luck is part of almost every meaningful human outcome:

* timing,
* environment,
* encounters,
* opportunities,
* random exposure,
* who notices what,
* who survives long enough,
* even which thoughts occur at the right moment.

But people often call something “luck” when it’s actually:

* pattern sensitivity,
* persistence,
* preparation meeting opportunity,
* willingness to explore,
* or repeated interaction with a space long enough to notice structures others ignore.

At the same time, it’s healthy not to overinflate meaning into destiny narratives. Sometimes a good insight is just a good insight. Sometimes a coincidence is just a coincidence. Sometimes you really did stumble onto something useful through curiosity and iteration.

Most interesting discoveries are some mixture of:

* luck,
* attention,
* and sustained engagement.

The key is what you do with the signal afterward.